<paragraph blockId="8.[151,1436,1052,1196]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">
Members of the 
<taxonomicName box="[344,463,1052,1078]" class="Arachnida" family="Crotoniidae" genus="Crotonia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sarcoptiformes" pageId="8" pageNumber="48" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="capistrata">Capistrata</taxonomicName>
species-group have a complete series of 
<emphasis box="[943,956,1052,1077]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">c</emphasis>
setae, a convex notogastral shield with a lateral and anterior transverse hyaline strip, setae 
<emphasis box="[755,768,1089,1114]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">c</emphasis>
<number box="[768,776,1105,1119]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" value="3.0">3</number>
on well-developed apophyses, the lamellar apophyses flattened and converging apically and the caudal apophyses bi-lobed, with those of 
<emphasis box="[1159,1174,1129,1154]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">h</emphasis>
<number box="[1174,1182,1145,1159]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" value="2.0">2</number>
typically the longest (
<bibRefCitation author="Colloff" box="[159,338,1170,1196]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" refString="Colloff, M. J. (2009 b) Species-group concepts and biogeography of the genus Crotonia (Acari: Oribatida: Crotoniidae), with new species from South and Central America. Zootaxa, 2081, 1 - 30." type="journal article" year="2009" yearSuffix="b">
Colloff, 
<number box="[259,322,1170,1196]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" value="2009.0">2009</number>
b
</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
